                <grid><![CDATA[]]></grid>
                <headline>Danish Presidency takes first step towards agreement on more transparent mortgage credit for EU consumers</headline>
                <intro><![CDATA[New EU rules require that providers of mortgage credit in the EU should ensure better information for consumers and more solid credit assessments for the receipt of mortgage credit. At the same time it will be easier for consumers to see where the best options are for them in taking out a mortgage. This is the heart of the new so-called Mortgage Credit Directive. The Danish Presidency is leading negotiations on the Directive, and has just received a mandate in the Council of Ministers to begin negotiations with the European Parliament.]]></intro>
                <body><![CDATA[
<p>A new Mortgage Credit Directive should help to a greater degree
to ensure that consumers receive advice on the mortgages they are
offered and take out. In addition the Directive creates more
transparency for consumers looking to choose a mortgage.</p>

<p>The Danish Presidency is leading negotiations of the Directive,
and has just received a mandate in the Council of Ministers to
begin negotiations with the European Parliament.</p>

<p>In concrete terms, the proposal introduces uniform requirements
for what information providers of mortgage credit should provide
for consumers in connection with taking out a loan for example for
buying a house, tougher rules for credit assessment of borrowers,
rules about competency requirements for loan providers as well as
rules on the provision of mortgages across borders within the
EU.</p>

<p>It shall ensure that consumers receive a high level of
information throughout the EU, and that consumers are to a greater
degree in a position to compare different providers of mortgages
across the market - and across national borders within the EU.</p>

<p>The Directive does not substantively change the existing Danish
rules, which already ensure that consumers receive a high level of
information and protection when they take out a mortgage.</p>

<p>Minister for Economic Affairs and the Interior, Margrethe
Vestager, says:</p>

<p>"I am satisfied that the Danish Presidency has achieved another
important result in the financial area, and that we have taken the
first step towards strengthening the requirements for mortgage
providers. We are strengthening consumers' ability to see through
the mortgage market and choose the loan which is best for
them."</p>

<p>"I expect the rules to contribute to more competition across
borders to the benefit of consumers in terms of taking out
mortgages, since the rules increase transparency and make it easier
for providers to offer loans across borders."</p>

<p>Minister of Business and Growth, Ole Sohn, says:</p>

<p>"We have seen in connection with the financial crisis that loans
have been given to consumers who did not have a solid enough
private economy. The new rules will contribute to avoiding
overindebtedness. This is an important element in relation to
supporting healthy economic development, preventing new financial
crises and supporting financial stability."</p>

<p>"In Denmark we already have rules in place on information and
advice for customers in regard of taking out mortgages. The
information requirements in the Directive are therefore not new in
a Danish context. It is very positive that we are now taking the
first step towards a raised level of investor protection in the
whole EU in this area, since developments on the mortgage market in
individual countries have an impact on economic developments in the
other countries."</p>

<p><strong>For further information, please contact:</strong></p>

<p>Press Secretary SørenMøller Nielsen, Ministry of Business and
Growth</p>

<p>Press Secretary Marie Nyhus, Ministry of Economic Affairs and
Interior</p>
]]></body>
